      <hedline>
        <hl1>Warner to Close Flagship</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Charles V. Bagli</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Bagli, Charles V</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Warner Brothers, four years after it doubled size of its flagship on Fifth Avenue, is closing studio store (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Four years after it doubled the size of its flagship on Fifth Avenue, Warner Brothers is closing the studio store.</p>
        <p>According to real estate executives, officials from Warner Brothers are expected to meet today with their landlord to finalize plans to terminate their lease for the store at Fifth Avenue and 57th Street.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Four years after it doubled the size of its flagship on Fifth Avenue, Warner Brothers is closing the studio store.</p>
        <p>According to real estate executives, officials from Warner Brothers are expected to meet today with their landlord to finalize plans to terminate their lease for the store at Fifth Avenue and 57th Street.</p>
        <p>Warner Brothers goods will still be sold at the three-story store in Times Square as well as downtown.</p>
        <p>The closing was first reported in Women's Wear Daily on Tuesday.</p>
        <p>Karine Joret, a spokeswoman for Warner Brothers, declined to comment, as did Allied Partners, the group that recently bought the building.</p>
        <p>Charles V. Bagli (NYT)</p>
        <p>METRO BUSINESS</p>
      </block>
